    "content": "Look, everyone wants to talk about the highlight reel. I want to talk about the foundation.\n\nWhen I evaluate talent at the highest level, I'm not looking for the player who can do the most moves. I'm looking for the player who can execute the right decision under pressure. That starts with how we train at the youth level.\n\n## Why Foundation-First Training Matters\n\nThe modern game demands cognitive speed. Your U16 athletes aren't just competing against their local conference anymore - they're being evaluated against a global talent pool. The difference between a player who advances and one who plateaus isn't complexity. It's consistency in executing fundamentals when fatigue sets in.\n\nBalance is the prerequisite for efficiency. Every drill we run has to answer one question: Does this raise her shooting percentage or decision-making speed?\n\n## The Core Development Stack\n\n### 1. The Transfer Triangle (Scoring Foundation)\n\n**Setup:** Player starts at the free throw line with ball, cone 3 feet in front, coach positioned at various spots around the arc.\n\n**Execution:**\n- Step around cone with proper footwork (inside foot leads)\n- Receive pass from coach\n- Execute shot with focus on energy transfer from feet through release\n- Land in same spot as takeoff (balance check)\n\n**Quality Cues:** \n- Wrist snaps down, not out\n- Follow-through holds until ball hits rim\n- No drift on landing\n\n**Progression:** Start stationary, add movement, then add defensive pressure\n\n**Volume:** 3 sets of 15 quality attempts from 3 different angles\n\n### 2. Mirror Decision Training (Cognitive Speed)\n\n**Setup:** Two players face each other, one ball between them\n\n**Execution:**\n- Leader makes slow, deliberate moves (jab step, shot fake, drive step)\n- Mirror matches every movement without the ball\n- Switch roles every 30 seconds\n- Progress to live 1v1 after 3 minutes of mirroring\n\n**Why This Works:** Forces players to read body language and react, not just execute pre-planned sequences\n\n**Quality Cue:** Mirror should move simultaneously, not reactively\n\n### 3. Pocket Control Series (Ball Security)\n\n**The Framework:** We're not training handles - we're training ball control under pressure.\n\n**Level 1 - Stationary Pocket Work:**\n- Ball stays between waist and shoulder\n- No pounding - just manipulation in space\n- 30 seconds each: front pocket, side pocket, protect pocket\n\n**Level 2 - Movement Integration:**\n- Same pocket positions while walking forward\n- Add change of pace (never speed, just tempo)\n\n**Level 3 - Pressure Application:**\n- Partner applies passive hand pressure\n- Maintain pocket control while pivoting\n\n**Common Mistake:** Players want to dribble low and hard. We want control and protection.\n\n## Age-Appropriate Scaling\n\n**13-14 Years:** Focus entirely on mechanics. No live competition until movements become automatic.\n\n**15-16 Years:** Add decision-making elements. Introduce time pressure and defensive reactions.\n\n**Advanced Players:** Layer in game-specific situations - coming off screens, attacking closeouts, transition decisions.\n\n## Implementation for Camp Directors\n\nStructure your training blocks in 20-minute segments:\n- Minutes 1-5: Foundation work (shooting form, footwork)\n- Minutes 6-15: Skill integration (combining moves with decisions) \n- Minutes 16-20: Competitive application (controlled scrimmage situations)\n\nThe investment you make in precise repetition at this age protects their development long-term. We're not just training basketball players - we're developing young women who understand that excellence is found in the details.\n\n## Coach's Corner\nWhen I work with elite players, I tell them the same thing I tell every U16 athlete: your journey is not a sprint, it's an investment. The habits you build now - the attention to detail, the commitment to consistency, the trust in the process - these become your competitive advantage.\n\nI've seen too many talented young players plateau because they skipped the foundation work. Don't let flashy drills fool you. The player who can execute a perfect pivot, make the right pass under pressure, and shoot with consistent mechanics will always outlast the player who just has good handles.\n\nRespect the process. Rule your spirit. Stay curious.\n\n— Adam Harrington, NBA Skills Coach",
